"Camera vocabulary from film, translated to (cine/*) and (world/camera-*)
verbs. Each shot type with a screenplay-style example.

Read this alongside chapter 6. Chapter 6 teaches the philosophy;
this appendix is the recipe book.

---

## Shot types

**WIDE (also called establishing)** — the whole room, all characters
visible. Purpose: orient the audience. Show relationships in space.

```scheme
(cine/shot 'wide 'room-center 60)
```

Screenplay: `WIDE ON THE PORCH. Two chairs. Mira and father sit.`

Use for scene openings, when a character joins the group, when the
audience needs to see who is where.

**MID (also called two-shot or medium)** — frames one or two
characters from the waist up. Purpose: dialogue focus without losing
context.

```scheme
(cine/shot 'mid mira 60)
;; or for two:
(cine/shot 'mid 'mira-and-father 90)
```

Screenplay: `MID SHOT — MIRA. She looks at her father.`

Use for most dialogue. This is the workhorse shot.

**CLOSE-UP** — frames head and shoulders. Purpose: emotional focus.
The audience sees micro-expressions.

```scheme
(cine/shot 'close-up mira 90)
```

Screenplay: `CLOSE ON MIRA. She hears the news.`

Use for the emotional peak of a scene. Do not overuse — every scene
does NOT need a close-up. Reserve for the moment that must land.

**EXTREME CLOSE-UP** — eyes, or mouth, or a single detail. Purpose:
maximum intensity.

```scheme
(cine/shot 'extreme-close-up 'mira-eyes 60)
```

Screenplay: `EXTREME CLOSE — MIRA'S EYES. Wet.`

Use very rarely. One or two per game. Overuse ruins the punch.

**OVER-SHOULDER** — camera behind one character, looking at another.
Purpose: subjective — audience sees what THIS character sees.

```scheme
(cine/shot 'over-shoulder :from father :at mira 60)
```

Screenplay: `OVER FATHER'S SHOULDER. He watches Mira read the letter.`

Use in dialogue when you want the audience to align with a specific
character's perspective.

**INSERT** — a shot of an object, not a character. Purpose: highlight
a detail.

```scheme
(cine/shot 'insert 'letter-on-table 45)
```

Screenplay: `INSERT — THE LETTER ON THE TABLE. Her mother's handwriting.`

Use for foreshadowing (Chekhov's gun), for reveals, for moments where
an object matters.

---

## Camera moves

**PAN** — camera swivels horizontally (or vertically) without moving
its position. Purpose: reveal what was offscreen, follow subject.

```scheme
(world/camera-pan-to 480 220 :duration 90)
```

Screenplay: `PAN LEFT to reveal the door. A figure stands in it.`

**PUSH-IN** — camera moves toward the subject. Purpose: escalating
intensity.

```scheme
;; Fake a push-in by targeting closer to the subject over time.
(world/camera-pan-to (entity/x mira) (entity/y mira) :duration 120)
(cine/shot 'close-up mira 60)   ;; end on close-up
```

Screenplay: `SLOW PUSH ON MIRA. Her expression does not change.`

**PULL-OUT** — camera moves away from subject. Purpose: reveal
context, sense of scale, isolation.

```scheme
(cine/shot 'wide 'room-center 60)   ;; from a close-up, pull to wide
```

Screenplay: `PULL BACK. Mira is alone in the huge kitchen.`

**FOLLOW** — camera tracks a moving subject.

```scheme
(cine/follow mira :ease 0.15)
;; or:
(world/camera-follow! mira :ease 0.15)
```

Screenplay: `MIRA walks toward the door. CAMERA FOLLOWS.`

**SHAKE** — camera vibrates. Purpose: shock, impact, unease.

```scheme
(world/camera-shake! 30 0.98)
```

Screenplay: `A LOUD SLAM. THE CAMERA SHAKES.`

**SNAP** — instant cut without move. Purpose: hard emotional beat.

```scheme
(world/camera-snap! (entity/x villain) (entity/y villain))
```

Screenplay: `CUT TO — VILLAIN'S FACE.`

---

## Recipe: the revelation shot

The classic five-shot sequence when something big is revealed.

```scheme
(define (revelation-shot subject reactor)
  ;; 1. Wide establishing.
  (cine/shot 'wide 'room 45)

  ;; 2. Insert on the object being revealed.
  (world/after 45
    (lambda () (cine/shot 'insert subject 60)))

  ;; 3. Cut to the reactor's face.
  (world/after 105
    (lambda () (cine/shot 'close-up reactor 90)))

  ;; 4. Hold on the reactor's expression change.
  ;; (No new shot; hold from previous.)

  ;; 5. Pull back to wide.
  (world/after 195
    (lambda () (cine/shot 'wide 'room 60))))
```

Wide, insert, close-up on reactor, hold, wide. Five seconds. Every
revelation in film uses some variation.

Screenplay:
```
WIDE ON THE ROOM. Everyone still.
INSERT — THE LETTER. It is her mother's handwriting.
CLOSE ON MIRA. She realizes what it is.
(HOLD)
WIDE ON THE ROOM. Nobody has moved.
```

---

## Recipe: the confrontation

Two characters face off. Camera cuts between them, tighter each time.

```scheme
(define (confrontation-cuts hero villain)
  ;; Round 1: medium on each.
  (cine/shot 'mid hero 60)
  (world/after 60 (lambda () (cine/shot 'mid villain 60)))

  ;; Round 2: close-up on each.
  (world/after 120 (lambda () (cine/shot 'close-up hero 45)))
  (world/after 165 (lambda () (cine/shot 'close-up villain 45)))

  ;; Round 3: extreme close-up on the hero.
  (world/after 210 (lambda () (cine/shot 'extreme-close-up hero 60))))
```

Nine seconds. Each cut is tighter. The audience feels the pressure
mounting. This is the shape of every western standoff and every
courtroom cross-examination.

---

## Recipe: the walk-and-talk

Two characters walk while talking. Camera tracks them from the side.

```scheme
(define (walk-and-talk hero friend)
  (motion/move-to hero  400 300 :duration 480)   ;; 8 seconds
  (motion/move-to friend 420 300 :duration 480)
  (cine/follow hero :ease 0.15)
  ;; Dialogue happens in on-frame while they walk.
  )
```

The camera follows the hero. The friend walks alongside. Dialogue
plays out over eight seconds of forward motion. The forward motion
itself is momentum — the audience feels the conversation moving
somewhere.

---

## Recipe: the empty room

A room after everyone has left. Camera holds still for a long beat.
No sound.

```scheme
(define (empty-room)
  (cine/shot 'wide 'kitchen 180)          ;; three-second hold
  (audio/halt)                             ;; silence
  ;; Nothing else. Just the empty room, held.
  )
```

Three seconds of empty room after a big scene. The audience feels
the absence. This is a shot you cannot do in a novel. Only cinema
and cinematic games can hold on emptiness.

---

## Recipe: the mirror shot

Two characters face each other. Camera cuts between them, then holds
on both in the same frame at the end.

```scheme
(define (mirror-shot a b)
  (cine/shot 'close-up a 60)
  (world/after 60 (lambda () (cine/shot 'close-up b 60)))
  ;; Now hold both in one frame.
  (world/after 120 (lambda () (cine/shot 'mid 'both-of-them 120))))
```

The audience saw each character's face separately. Now they see them
together. The shift into the shared frame signals connection —
they are now sharing an experience the audience witnessed
individually.

---

## Recipe: the reveal-through-cut

Character says something. Camera cuts to what they said about.

```scheme
(define (reveal-through-cut)
  (cine/shot 'close-up mira 60)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"MIRA: 'And then I saw the note.'\")
  ;; She looks toward the counter.
  (part/look-toward mira 400 300)
  ;; Cut to the counter.
  (world/after 90
    (lambda ()
      (cine/shot 'insert 'note-on-counter 90))))
```

Mira mentions the note. She looks toward it. Cut to the note. The
audience follows her attention. This is basic film grammar; kids
absorb it instantly when they see it.

---

## What to avoid

**Over-cutting.** More than six cuts in a two-minute scene and the
audience gets tired. Long takes are underused in games; try them.

**Shakes during dialogue.** The text becomes unreadable. Shake
between lines, never underneath.

**Following EVERY movement.** Sometimes the camera should hold still
while a character walks OUT of frame. That is its own effect — the
audience feels the loss.

**Push-ins during quiet moments.** A slow push-in is high drama.
Using it during a casual conversation feels overwrought.

**Snap-cuts during monologues.** A long monologue wants long takes.
Cutting every three seconds during a soliloquy is exhausting.

---

## Summary

Six shot types (wide, mid, close-up, extreme close-up, over-shoulder,
insert). Six camera moves (pan, push-in, pull-out, follow, shake,
snap). Six recipes (revelation, confrontation, walk-and-talk, empty
room, mirror, reveal-through-cut).

That is the vocabulary. Learn it once; use it forever.")
